  "prompt": "How many scientists believe in Evolution?",
  "response": "The vast majority of scientists, particularly those in the fields of biology, genetics, paleontology, and related disciplines, accept the theory of evolution as the foundational framework for understanding the diversity of life on Earth. This consensus is supported by extensive evidence from multiple lines of scientific inquiry, including fossil records, comparative anatomy, molecular biology, and genetics.\n\nWhile it is challenging to provide an exact percentage, surveys and studies consistently indicate that upwards of 95% to 99% of scientists in relevant fields support the theory of evolution. For example, a 2009 Pew Research Center survey found that 97% of scientists in the United States agreed that humans and other living things have evolved over time.\n\nIt is important to note that acceptance of evolution is not a matter of belief but rather of understanding and interpreting the evidence. The theory of evolution, as proposed by Charles Darwin and refined by subsequent research, is one of the most robust and well-supported theories in the scientific community. However, like all scientific theories, it is subject to further testing and refinement as new evidence emerges.",
